A Republican strategy to counter Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have identified only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in the last ten years.
One thing is certain: these new arrangements will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for organizing the federal elections in the US.
In this spirit, a majority of US governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 that made the process of registering or voting more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
The laws also reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on election day and deprive citizens with criminal records of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities quickly extended this practice to other states.
In the last two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo IDs issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
Often, however, it costs more than $100 to obtain the required identification.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more than that.
Students, voters considered to be more likely to vote for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their institution-issued photo IDs.
On the other hand, those same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more Republican to use the cards issued by those clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
Now, it turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in 2011 sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register some 10 million citizens.
Measures adopted since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the rate of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators passed laws in five other states to reduce the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early voters were African-American, while African-Americans made up only 13% of the state's voters.
The same thing happened with Hispanics.
They represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, whites, who made up 76% of voters, made up only 46% of early voters.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The Attorney General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit some of the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed laws requiring photo IDs.
Nevertheless, the new rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new arrangements will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Testing for prostate cancer - pass or fail?
The APS test may sometimes give false negative or false positive results, resulting in unnecessary medical intervention.
This makes men who are already reluctant to take the test even more reluctant.
Pass the test or not?
We asked two experts for their opinion.
In studies in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it's difficult to interpret this data and make firm recommendations.
Another study, the European one, found a difference in mortality between patients who had been tested and those who had not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that you have a 30 to 40 percent greater chance of metastasis if you're not screened.
So I recommend testing at age 50, or at age 40 if you have a direct relative who has had prostate cancer before.
African-American men are also at higher risk.
The key is to make the right decision once you've been diagnosed with cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
We really need to make the patient understand the risk of his cancer, by offering him the options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that are not life-threatening, and instead, in those cases, opting for active disease surveillance.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and life-threatening.
We're going to suggest that they be actively monitored, and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
Increasingly, there is a strict definition of what criteria should be used to decide who should or should not be treated.
So I still recommend you take the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine whether or not you should pass it.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of the APS test.
This document can be downloaded (in English for now, a translation will be available shortly) at: http://ca.movember.com/en/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for cancer.
Despite the advances in research, good habits remain the best way to reduce the risk of suffering from it.
It's estimated that if everyone ate right and got enough exercise, we could prevent 30 percent of all cancers.
"If no one smoked anymore, the rate would rise to at least 50 percent", says André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
On the other hand, it is estimated that about 10 percent of cancers are caused by heredity.
Many remain completely unexplained.
The Canadian Cancer Society continues to make tobacco control a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Cigarette smoking is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for many others.
This is a huge health risk.
"There are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec", laments spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouraging fact: Ten years after quitting, the risk of dying from cancer drops by half.
Weight
Obesity and obesity also contribute to the onset of the disease, according to the CCS.
They would increase the risk of breast, colon and rectum, esophagus, pancreas and uterine cancer.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against colon cancer", it adds.
The food
The WHO also recommends limiting consumption of red meat.
Too much of it increases the risk of colorectal cancer.
So are the meat shops, and they should be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting may lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"These can damage the body's cells and lead to the development of cancer", they explain.
The vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin supplements and cancer.
Their research, however, is not conclusive at this time.
Studies on vitamin E are conflicting, according to the SCC.
While one woman noted a decrease in the risk of prostate cancer, another noted an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer is also not well established.
In addition, Mr Beaulieu stresses the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
"Studying for cancer doesn't mean you have cancer".
The Higgs boson has been de-orbited.
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
This is because we believe that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more.
And then, this is the last particle that is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a genuinely new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data released this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but we still lack the data to be absolutely sure.
Let's just say that it's the Higgs, because the chances of getting it wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is a law in this underworld that cannot be broken. Two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule - and don't try too hard, you'll hurt yourself.
But even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From this, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And the other is about bosons, a nasty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything -- at least not that principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure website at Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson is in some way related.
These bosons, it should be pointed out here, are not all as exotic as you might think.
In fact, if you are able to read this column, it is because of a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or "light particle", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at that particular point, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disorder" comes an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that it's another field, the Higgs field, that has to be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a little like a frozen pond, which only a very large rock could wrinkle the surface.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometer ring! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never stand on its own on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, you know) don't.
Now, what can all this research "bring", asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between the observations and predictions of the MS.
Many are eager to see it, because the slightest difference could open the door to a "new physics" and close some holes in the Model.
It has, it must be said, still huge flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (oops!).
But we haven't found such discrepancies at CERN until now.
The effects
The impact of this research on the daily lives of Mr and Mrs All-World is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
Look, back in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser technology at Bell Labs had no idea what a revolution their work was going to spark.
They were seeing some scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we've been told by the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - that at first the laser was seen more as a "laboratory gadget".
Can you imagine?
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, in 1969, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work on optics.
This sensor, although not at all what he originally intended, is now used as the "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and it won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
That doesn't mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Commission to die with dignity, Quebec has recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
But much remains to be done in this vital area.
The Duty tried to look more closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his Montérégie apartment.
He had been suffering from prostate cancer for two years.
"They had given me five years to live, I made seven", he said, half fig half grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the night before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that", he says.
The disease is working: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone, and even eating alone.
He sits down to a delicious lunch, and he accepts help to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even smiles, talks to strangers who rush around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for the disease.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man urinates standing up", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
To return to the childhood stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept regression, he says.
Because, according to many people working in palliative care, great moments are happening at the very heart of this regression.
The patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home are all cancer patients.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called 'curative' care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is dying "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease has made me discover my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life", she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for the last visit of her son from Italy in the next few days.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide body care and food assistance.
It's palliative care, which is what you give when there's nothing else to do.
To make the death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we're all going to die one day.
Here life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the house's doctors.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
On the dying, we'll accept brandy or Pepsi mouthwash, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served Mr. X a beer, and he died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help the family as well as the patients", says Nathalie Savard, a director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, days follow but are not alike.
With a 93-year-old man enjoying his last family gathering in the yard, well-dressed in his pillows as a toast is made in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For six months now, there have been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under 45 years of age", says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the end of his life, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Victor-Gadbois House and the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great shortage in Quebec's health care system that has many palliative care doctors fearing the passing of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by top palliative care officials including Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not good enough to ensure that everyone will have access to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
She says that recently I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without any help.
I'm afraid some patients only ask to die because they don't get the right care.
And at the same time, many oncologists are working hard on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helen Richard's chances of survival were already slim when she gave up a grueling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she said she was sorry I stopped fighting, she said.
She told me I was finished!
Not the Almighty
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank their caregivers for not granting their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But palliative care is not the absolute all-powerful way to treat pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are unwilling to accept pain-relieving treatments in 8 percent of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is the practice of putting the patient to sleep until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend anymore that we don't hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the option of having this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me", it means "I want to be relieved".
