Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Road officials, BTP contractors, political party fundraisers and Italian mafia specialists tell us day after day what they know about a formidable "system" that includes the construction industry, civil servants, politicians, trade unionists and mafia.
This "industry" has cost Quebec taxpayers dearly, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's funny how the system has been crumbling since we took the big shot", says Jacques Duchesneau, a Quebec legislator and former Montreal police chief.
He was the one who caused the scandal in 2011, through a thorough investigation into mismanagement of road works contracts in Quebec, which the Liberal Prime Minister at the time, Jean Charest, had only backed off.
The Duchesneau report established a direct link between industry, covert party financing and government corruption.
"Since the start of the investigation in 2010, the Department of Transport alone has reportedly saved a billion dollars on contracts", he points out, some of them restraining their instincts to get a quota!
The Charbonneau Commission "has already brought down two mayors", he adds, hoping that it will succeed in "demonstrating the schemes behind the individuals".
A permanent anti-corruption unit established in 2011
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, established in 2011, is also working with its army of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
Plus the police of the "Hammer Squad" who, since 2009, have led the "sewer cartel" of Montreal to put the soft pedal on the inflation of contracts...
In recent weeks, it has carried out a series of searches and brought charges of fraud and corruption against municipal elected officials, such as Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, mayor of a suburban town.
Next on the list would be Gilles Vaillancourt, who has just resigned as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of repeatedly taking bribes in exchange for public contracts.
The charges also include Montreal road engineers and Italian-born contractors, including Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito.
The latter caused a sensation by explaining to the committee the mechanics of the 'system' of obtaining public contracts.
He himself spent years paying 3% of the value of the contracts obtained in Montreal to a mafia-linked intermediary who poured the money into Union Montréal, the party of Mayor Gérald Tremblay.
Mr Zambito has been sowing wildfire in the 2000s, giving over C$88,000 (about €68,000) to provincial parties, mainly the then-ruling Liberals.
He also confessed to organizing an illegal fundraiser for former Liberal deputy prime minister Nathalie Normandeau.
Sewer contracts he inflated the cost of
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption was running wild.
Gilles Surprenant, a former civil engineer, explained to the commission: "In ten years, he received gifts from construction companies, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey games, and bribes totalling $736,000 in exchange for contracts for sewage treatment, which he inflated".
Other road officials admitted to getting fat by inflating bills by 30 to 40 percent with false extras.
Then a party organizer for the mayor, Martin Dumont, accused Mr Tremblay of deliberately turning a blind eye to a side budget that fed his coffers with dirty money.
Following these revelations, Mr. Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a major crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first elected officials in Montreal to sound the alarm.
Mayor of the Rivière-des-Prairies district, in the east of the island, she rebelled in 2010 against the sale of a municipal land bought for 5 million dollars and sold... 1.6 million to developers, in the middle of the real estate boom.
70% dirty money in election campaigns
Of the investigation that will eventually be set up, she says she is "pulling on a thread to understand how the system, infiltrated by ants, works to stop the gangrene and pin the culprits".
The process, she says, is "painful but positive".
We're cleaning up the wound, but we'd need a Montreal-based investigative unit and a watch to keep the shady practices from returning.
How we clean up.
I do it regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau, for his part, notes that "officials have stolen hundreds of millions of dollars", but is especially concerned about the role of "elected officials who know the plot", when they are not immersed in the ruse!
Estimating that 70% of the money used in Quebec's election campaigns is dirty money, he ironically says: "I was told that it was just a pale reflection of reality".
The Quebec government proposes to limit party donations to $100 but this will not change the situation, he says: "Until we strictly limit electoral spending, there will be dirty money in politics".
He advocates a complete overhaul of the system of public procurement and party financing: "We cannot go any lower; going to the bottom of things, with courage, will allow us to rebuild the house on a stronger foundation, with more controls and laws".
If this story tarnishes the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau invites those who laugh at it to look in their own backyard...
