With Bitcoin, Pay and Sell Without Banks
The opposite of the current monetary exchange, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from peer to peer.
Some 200 000 transactions have already been recorded on 15 000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a high of $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Not very impressive, compared to the world's trade in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is distinguished from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", which are used to advance in a video game that is earned by playing or that can be purchased (and sometimes exchanged in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both ledger keepers, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the manner of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins are in the public ledger, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to the computers, and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that extra line.
This is a file hashing phase, which is the transformation of a large file into a shorter, unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" the whole thing.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes can easily verify that it's the right number.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, in order to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other being orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided in two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, leaving a margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also increased with each increase in computing power.
Life on the network has had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The flaw used is not related to the protocol itself", assures Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also points to the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, "giant soldiers" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who also wrote a textbook on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a network for transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are thus cheaper.
The user also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is give an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement away from hierarchical systems towards more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point", he predicts.
The ECB also plans in its report to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, in the event of the success of this currency.
