A Constitution in forceps in Egypt
It's another poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever about the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, it has decided to play it safe.
He took everyone by surprise when he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this House two more months to finish its work.
For almost two years, Egypt has relied on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which has weakened institutional stability and led to legal problems.
This new initiative has only increased the division in the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample the law".
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a regulation on the protection of the environment.
A referendum should be held within the next fortnight.
A very short period of time that forced the Brothers to abandon their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems confident that Egyptians will vote in favour, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
This is especially true since the use of a hasty vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I retain full powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the declaration of the constitution, they had slammed the door, feeling that they had not been able to make their views known.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order to reach the necessary quorum, 11 alternate members were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, the majority of the articles were voted unanimously.
Some commentators have even made fun of the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around the time of the prayer, with some members of the committee feeling that the clock of the constituency was mis-set.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
The subject of all attention, Article 2 is ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the principal source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", the Liberals reply, seeing it as a mere communication.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular as regards the verification of the compliance of the laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "people who are called upon to make their own decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
It is the beginning of a theocracy".
The Liberals are also concerned that the next rector of this university will be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulama but academics, some of whom are trained in the French system", says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity about Article 220, because the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
References to fiqh are made, especially to Islamic jurisprudence.
And the question may be raised in the future as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule on it".
The text adopted yesterday is not only religious in nature but also widely criticized because of the extensive powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of dispute was the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will the military courts be allowed to try civilians, as human rights groups have called for.
The latter also expressed their concerns about the text, which they considered liberticidal.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly for the press.
Moreover, no news articles are more about women's protection, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
The only positive point, she said, was the Article 36 ban on torture.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are looking forward to holy sites, the World Centre and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of Bible truths, modern comforts, and wildlife.
Argoumenty i Fakty has picked five main reasons for you to go to Israel.
Go worship at the holy places
Go to the Jordan River where Jesus was baptizing.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptism depths" will be touched by divine grace.
And Galilee is the land of Jesus' miracles - where he turned water into wine, where he walked on water, where he calmed the wind, or where he miraculously caught fish.
It was there that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But where you'll find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
The faithful walk along the Rue de la Suffrance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins near the Fortress of Antonia (the Praetorian Palace), where the trial was held, and then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, and then to that of the Anointing Stone and the tomb.
Here is the center of the Christian world, the symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is built on the spot where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site of the Jews: the Wailing Wall, which is the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave short words with prayers that are then answered.
Flying high
Visit the ruins of the fortress of Massada, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 B.C. for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineers can go there on their own.
For others, a cable car takes them to this historic peak.
In the north of the country, between 1 600 and 2 040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mount Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are 45 km long.
Old beliefs say that pagan gods once dwelt on the mountain's summit.
Visit some unique museums
There are nearly 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit them all in one trip.
Here are five of the most interesting ones that are worth a visit.
First, the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the ancient Qumran Manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in caves in the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The exhibition is mainly devoted to the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths made of mouldings of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guidebooks or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial in Tel Aviv, which is a re-enactment of the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk in and you're in total darkness.
The stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaports lie along the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea, and the Dead Sea.
Each of these has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and giant aquariums.
Note: You can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, since the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees Celsius while the air temperature can reach 23 degrees Celsius.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world - it is the lowest point on Earth, at 417 meters below sea level.
The blue-colored water is salty and easily trapped by swimmers, even those who cannot swim.
The landscapes around it are surreal.
People come to the temple to perform saltwater, lime, and mud treatments and to treat various ailments, such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and simply to relax.
Unlock the secrets of the ancient world
They are guarded by the ancient city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is traversed by the famous Via Maris, which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists especially enjoy walking along the narrow lanes named after the zodiac signs.
They say if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theater, "conquering" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Caesarea was the capital of the Roman Empire of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you are going to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to use dollars rather than euros, since they are easily exchanged for shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly by bus, but Jerusalem has a fast tram system, and Haifa has the only six-station metro line in the country, which connects the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost like an underground funicular.
The fare for all types of public transport is 6 shekels and you can make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to observe the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transportation are closed.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
There are a variety of dishes made from lamb and beef, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, as well as hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, various sauces, ground chickpeas, falafel, fruit and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are many well-fed cats that walk around looking arrogant.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats like to be in the middle of nowhere and they don't mind being treated.
The price of a car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
The average entrance to the museum is 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
Most of them were travelers and holidaymakers from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on 9 February 2011.
"Who has a language, goes to Moscow": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are debating what the law on the compulsory language test will bring, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Each year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are from Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families back home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force that requires every migrant worker to pass a Russian language test.
At the moment, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the service, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, in time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, as well as Russian history and the foundations of law, will need to be validated.
You will need to validate your knowledge of Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian is an official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained teaching certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Peoples' Friendship University, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders had already asked the question in the press many times: What will it do?
What will the requirement to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, the immigration officials say, it will reduce the number of people suffering "slavery at work".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems are for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without the language, says Sebelev, the prospective migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "trip" to a crowded cottage where he and dozens of his fellow workers will languish for months without food and paper and will have to work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We've been getting a lot of complaints from our immigrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, their passports are taken, and they do not receive the expected salary", confirms the Head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many Central Asian citizens who wish to come to Russia to earn money admit that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to visit but also have difficulty writing in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, or Tajiks can afford to attend even a decent primary school.
Their families cannot even feed their children, let alone dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, they go out to earn money at the first opportunity.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished".
Human Rights activists note, however, one important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be for migrants with legal status only.
Without a status, there will be no examination or official work afterwards.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or no entry"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money - between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know we have false documents, we have no record, hence the extortion cases.
"They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, to buy cigarettes and tea", Oumed Khouchkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
"Hurry up, don't be lazy and buy yourself a beautiful work of art"
From the first day of the language law, it was discovered that not only the immigrant registration papers were fake.
Several false language test certificates have already been confiscated by the Federal Migration Service.
The counterfeit paper comes from a regular color printer.
Of course, their new owners were not disappointed. Each migrant who hoped to make the exam easier had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The government officials and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper pieces".
The authorities may give migrant workers who failed the first examination time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The proportion of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes toughening the law against civilian gun owners.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents, from the shooting at weddings to the murder by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which left seven dead.
Police want to ban the carrying of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the State Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the law on weapons would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see the Russian authorities trying to solve the problem by "screwing the screw".
An open letter has appeared on the Internet in which the authors, representatives of various firing centers, demand that "this senseless hardening" be abandoned.
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime expert for the BBC, told Russia's state-run news agency.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a registered firearm in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the tightening of laws on civilian weapons will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon at a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: From the factory to the officer
The black market for weapons is provided through several channels.
There are five main channels, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and at Headquarters.
Screenshot from a gun-control site
The first is the "military trace", i.e. the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians", Baranets explains.
The second type of black market weapon is the one that criminals steal from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
The illegal guns are being sold from military warehouses.
Many of these have been frequently blown up.
"There are verified reports that some fires were set deliberately to cover up the shortfall", explains the former soldier.
Baranets thinks the weapons manufacturers are responsible for something.
"We see private arms factories that are not competing on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow", says one expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A large proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply", adds the former soldier.
Where do the guns come from?
Experts have estimated the approximate share of each source of illegal arms on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records, and public data from weapons-related websites.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the guns on the black market ended up there "because of employees whose work is related to guns", explains the report.
According to the researchers, 17 percent of guns are from military conflict sites, 14 percent are stolen at the time of manufacture, and 5 percent are from "clandestine leaks".
A dealer and consultant at a gun-shop who asked to remain anonymous assured that the weapons found by these specialists in clandestine excavations had long been out of stock.
He said that most often, the sellers go to military warehouses to get the new goods.
The person purchases a unit through a sign, for example a TT pistol.
We deliver it to him by passing the merchandise through a grid.
"He takes it to the city and sells it for 900 euros per unit with two chargers", he says.
