"At the moment, we can only fool the brain on average"
Recently, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to seeing augmented reality through special glasses.
At first, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it is clear from the interview with the director of the interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft Labs in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists at this company, glasses are already ancient history.
They're tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained for the moment with pixels on flat screens and sometimes touch.
