- Although the Kinect has rendered physical interaction, a lot of things happen on flat screens, sometimes in 3D.
Information capture has been improved (the system receives more data), but the efficiency, for the moment, not so much.
We're trying to change that, and we're working on truly 3D imaging systems that run on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to bring the computing world into our own, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
This, however, requires identifying not only the user but also the space around him.
So we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical way.
And for starters, let's get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command ?
She's appreciated, but isn't she overrated?
This is not the panacea. The question of confidentiality arises because we do not always want to inform others of our actions or intentions.
In fact, every kind of computer interaction is good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control the devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discrete, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera on the device, but by a hand-held bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It's currently large, but it's theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can to you?
You would do it with words and with gestures.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's going to be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or can't do at a given time?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
It could be, for example, laser sensors, they produce a pretty good resolution in depth and that's very important.
- If we're interested in your work on the Xbox Kinect sensors, what do you dislike about modern cameras?
Is it that they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, it is the current generation that we rely on in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to that last point, all the current technologies are pretty good, which adds work to the algorithm designers.
The resolution must be kept in mind in terms of the X and Y axes, but also the Z axes.
Speed is also very important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond laboratory, has given touch sensors a steady processing delay of between 1 and 100 μs, with current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
