- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the common mortal.
There is one problem that opponents of this idea point to: there is no tactile sensation!
My hands can't feel a thing!
What responses is your group preparing to this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth might very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
One of the most interesting techniques at the moment is the use of the second hand as a picture medium.
It's a perfect record of pressure!
But there are also technologies which are really designed to give palpability to these "images in the air": for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is and which gives you the sensation, at the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of your fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that affect the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a work axis that presents perspectives.
- And you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think he feels what he should feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried it yet.
There is still a task below that will take a long time to solve: how to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that he is walking in an almost infinite open space - we are working on the concepts of running mats (not like those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we are only moderately successful at deceiving the brain, and there are still many years of work to be done.
That's what makes working on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: a lot of things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
