Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or a deadly asteroid collision.
Space shuttle caravans with Earthlings aboard are leaving in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: How do we keep our species living in weightlessness or on a backup planet?
I don't think there's much to choose from.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only hypothetically.
"These are Venus and Mars", says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Institute for Astronomy (GAICh).
If conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500 degrees.
It's only habitable at very high altitudes or on the orbit of Venus... in space.
We started to get interested in the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were being done on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit were in no way different from the terrestrial varieties.
Then, insects were put into orbit, tiny fly-eating, breeding dross.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how an unweighted embryo develops.
You get a perfectly normal chick on the way out.
Then the problems start.
"The problem is that the chick needs to find a support, get on its feet and start moving", explains Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory at the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
With no support, the chicks roamed in disorderly ways.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks didn't react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We gouged out their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it's just impossible to work with them there", explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the Bion biosatellite will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, we have not discovered anything supernatural.
"We were still using biosatellites and this is the only experiment we have done, and we have to do this kind of research", says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, reproductions directly in space are not yet possible.
It's not a small matter.
With the loss of their natural habitat, animals are no longer able to fulfill their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, man is capable of this, in principle.
Homo sapiens have abstract thinking, they can create a proper emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been going to space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is the most precious thing that humanity has.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would survive a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the robbery.
"No one answered this question", explains Vakhtang Vatchnadzé, a retired rocket and space industry expert.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a baby girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after having twice been in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk remains.
We have few, very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and give birth to healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it is dangerous even in orbit", concludes the Soviet hero and Russian hero, the pilot and cosmonaut Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet, mankind must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection, and the creation of artificial gravity.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonaut Training Centre: compulsory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, the cosmonauts are training for extra-vehicular sorties.
Water imitates weightlessness.
While water is a comfortable but alien environment for adults, it is a true element for infants.
The little amphibians seem to confirm that life on Earth originated in the ocean.
Since the baby develops in the lymphatic fluid of the mother's womb for about nine months, it is easier for it to get used to water.
This makes sense, since from birth to the first bath, it's only two weeks.
"It's very little to forget", explains Marina Aksenova, a swimming instructor for infants.
In short, if for the newborn child weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravity, a force of gravity.
When weightless, the muscles of the abdomen, the pelvis, atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
Okay, let's ignore that by relying on the birth simulators.
Of course, we can prepare a delivery in a special room, the woman will be able to get him out.
"And then?" asks Valery Poliakov, inviting us to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
If it doesn't feel the pull of the earth, the body doesn't form the skeleton or the muscle system.
You can't dress an infant like an adult in a special training suit.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experiment, which we would imagine in this case, imagining the birth of a child in an alien environment, will result in the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely unadapted", predicts Igor Pestov, Director of the Bioethics Committee of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
The birth of children in space is still a theory.
However, in time, this will become a reality, as Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the home of their spaceman-born offspring.
The head of the ISC (Superior Institution for the Control of Public Finance) said: "The control of the pseudo-self-employed (in Czech 'Svarc system') has failed because of the politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation but lagged behind in its enforcement.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, the vice-president of the Higher Institution for Public Finance Control in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and, in my opinion, that is what is lacking in our country", Kala said in his commentary on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the approach of the "Švarc system" by Petr Nečas.
The Prime Minister recently said that the SDGs would not bother entrepreneurs with controls; is that permissible or prohibited?
"The law must be enforced in some way, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect and demand compliance with the law", Kala said.
At the meeting of the Committee on Auditors in the Chamber of Deputies you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was the specific issue ?
This is a parallel control which we started about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for the way public procurement is managed and for specific national legislation and practice to follow.
We have collected all this and although this control procedure is not yet complete, we have found some very interesting differences: generally speaking, our legislation may be 'harder and of better quality', but according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to develop more and more detailed rules on a continuous basis, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project help you in practice and what are the results for you?
This is a common control which should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when it is not having a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest) in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering the market thresholds may not achieve this objective.
It may be that the system is so overwhelmed with paperwork that those looking for flaws in it will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our ISC or a different way of organising it?
As regards the institutions, similar to the ISC, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there, which is similarly organised, and also has a slightly differently constituted council, but these two institutions operate in a fundamentally similar manner.
The powers are also to some extent similar, with one nuance in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure, so it also has accounting courses of this type at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which in our country is equivalent to state resources.
The public funds managed by the regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of the Länder' accounting rates.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, but in certain areas Germany is often cited as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that it is doing better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, I'm sure not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we regard as a model, is also faced with a whole series of problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As regards national legislation, what has the amendment of the law on public procurement meant for you as an institution? Are its effects already being felt?
This amendment is relatively recent in coming into force and has not yet had an impact on our control operations.
We are doing ex post checks, so there is a delay.
Our observations concern only the preparation process for future checks at the moment - we have launched a new 'mismanagement risk detection' tool with which we have screened almost 14 000 public procurement contracts - where these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been changed and the conditions for certain types of tender procedures and so on.
So do you see the passing of this law as an advantage or as an additional burden on the administration?
I think this legislation is a step in the right direction and I hope the future will confirm it.
The problem is that these rules become more stringent and it is not possible to comply with them.
Under the previous rules, the provider (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the procurement law constituted a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really worth making the law tougher this way?
No, not like that, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who commit formal errors without impact on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what's the solution?
Let's see where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDGs would not bother entrepreneurs with so-called Švarc system controls - what does that mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or authorised?
The law must be enforced in some way, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from inspecting and enforcing the law.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it", but he can't say that we're going to act like nothing happened.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on formalities to be carried out, precisely in order to protect the tendering process.
But it is also tragic that a tenderer is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be just and that is what I think we lack.
