Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the European Space Agency's Ministers, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years has participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's journey into space, however, began much earlier.
Even before World War II, enthusiastic Poles were working on space flights, and they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw on December 6, 1933, in which he presented ideas from his groundbreaking book entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left listeners cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The late Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great proponent of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned proponent of astronomy, his contribution being rewarded in particular by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925 a dredge was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was intended to propel or brake the drain.
The only information known about this drain is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the archives that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937 plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects to use rocket technology were led by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the outbreak of war put an end to its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne (Polish Astronautical Society).
The first mention of a company was in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problème, which contained four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to the
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the autumn the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This 1,800-meter-long rocket was 80 centimeters long and weighed just under five kilograms.
An improved version, RM-1A, was subsequently built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were begun in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kilograms.
The next prototype should have been capable of performing concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM type rockets.
This two-stage rocket had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A had a space offering a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a 10 kg payload at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut in this programme.
