In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student protesters stormed the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, for it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
This was a blow to the prestige of the United States, compounded later by the failure of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organised by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle was a major contributor to the defeat of Jimmy Carter by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, depicts an episode of this story that brought a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After a few complicated adventures, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran under a cloak: they left the country with Canadian passports as part of a film crew to do spot-shoots for a major science fiction film.
Combination of the genders
The plan by exfiltration expert Tony Mendez required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the legend more credible, specialist magazines reported on the film project, press conferences were held, and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, as the film was based on the memoirs of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is partly a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a betrayal - as, for example, in the Ocean's Eleven, Twelve and Thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres are in succession: documentary-style footage of Tehran (under-titled footage features iconic photographs of the time of the events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no major differences),
Some lighter Hollywood scenes, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with men in costumes discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director, and his acting no longer drew ridicule.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark crime drama Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The Town (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not set in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that set his early films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the word.
He does it very well, sometimes he adds some elements to reality and the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway is quite hairy).
The weakness of Argo is its dissipative nature, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their roles as Hollywood co-workers, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are far from the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it is shown with moderate interest, appreciating the direction and retro style of the 70s.
He's pulling the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a still, in a way, unfinished story to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the Secret Service as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the trick.
Rules for balloons, bananas and circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which conducts an annual public survey of the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch a competition for the most absurd regulations or ideas from the "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is considering adopting a quota of 40 percent of women for the management of large European companies has been the reason for our decision", said the organiser of the survey, Patrik Nacher, to the newspaper Právo.
Among the absurdities mentioned is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have been at an advantage in terms of life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, less risk for insurance companies.
People can report any other idea of the EU workshop that is as incredible as this until the end of the year.
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013", Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the obligation to add bio-based fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition of using reliable mercury thermometers, simply because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticism has also been voiced in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term 'sweet butter' or the withdrawal of conventional light bulbs from sale.
The quality bananas must be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (the Czech Republic is currently imposing its banks' demands by threatening to use its veto).
The interests of the lobbying groups are also behind the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an 'abnormal curve'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonising non-homogeneous national standards which complicated trade.
Standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, which claim that existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize in this survey may be awarded to last year's EU regulation that inflatable balloons must bear a warning that children under 8 years of age should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU referred to a US survey which found that balloons are the leading cause of death by suffocation among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under 14 years of age when blowing in fair trumpets.
We have strange ideas at home too.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this subject to Greece, anyone holding an official position within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez Faire" of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com named in this survey, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for the stocks of foodstuffs that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, then exceeded the quantities set for canned mushrooms and thus faced a heavy fine.
The organisers of this survey found it interesting to pay money to certain countries because they have no access to the sea and to grant a grant to apply for a grant.
These ideas, however, do not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"The fact that we don't have a sea is a handicap.
We will ask the European Union for a refund.' This was the view expressed in autumn 2004 by the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, because of our wheat production, and as a result of the so-called 'interventionist' purchases, the State had been left with full stocks which it had then had to export.
Palas said the EU should have given us millions of euros because the Czech Republic is far from ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech request and organised a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without sea access.
The grants for the grant were offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), and were to be used in the preparation of applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "Weird regulations are rare".
While regulations are often criticised in the Member States, many experts say the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effective functioning of the Union and its overall development are worthy of praise.
More serious, for example, according to experts, is the problem of the use of EU grants for projects which have nothing whatsoever to do with the strengthening of European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States during budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a fight which it does not always win) is a source of great emotion for the Czechs.
If after six years of fighting the Germans and the Austrians the Czechs successfully defended the name 'Olomoucké tvarůžky', our producers had to replace the name 'Tuzemský rum' with the name 'Tuzemák' as it was known to us in the 19th century.
Only products made from cane sugar alcohol, not from beet sugar, may bear the name 'rum'.
The official EU list of registered products now includes globally known cheeses such as feta or Gorgonzola, Lübeck cheese or Parma ham, Karlovy Vary biscuits ("Karlovarské suchary"), Pohořelice and Třeboň carps ("Pohořelický a Třeboňský kapr") and Žatec hops ("Žatecký chmel").
The Pardubický perník spice bread and the cakes called "Cornets de Hořice" ("hořické trubičky") can also be proud of their Community brand.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how do we come up with the idea of running for president?
It's not being a senator or president that matters to me.
If everything was running smoothly in our country, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can no longer bear to see the country being plundered for the last 20 years, that thieves are not locked up and taxes and retirement age are increasing.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, then I try to come up with a solution to change it.
And since I am over 40 and independent, not a member of any party, I have no other choice but to run for president or senate.
You entered the Senate but quickly made your way to the Castle.
Don 't you turn your backs on those who have chosen you ?
I always said I'd go into battle for the castle based on the results of the Senate elections.
Later, I made it clear that if I was elected to the Senate, I would run for president.
My purpose is not the function, this is just a tool that allows me to realize my vision.
That is why I need the greatest influence and the widest mandate.
The problem is not just that we as a nation are rallying in bars or in front of our television stations, but that we are trampling on those who are trying to make a difference.
Added to this is the press, which is defaming people and confusing free speech with freedom to lie.
For example, it has been claimed that I am bribing journalists or that I was an adviser to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's get to your visions.
You started the fight for the Castle with the themes of material and criminal liability of politicians and retroactive tax returns beyond twenty million [CZK].
You must change the law to that end.
As president, you don't have that power, and only the Senate as a whole can propose legislation.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When I, as a citizen, pushed for tourist guides to be a liberal profession, I won.
The problem is politics: when someone comes from the left or the right with a good project, it is knowingly rejected and it delays the citizens.
As an independent, member of no party, I have a much better chance of winning the support of all the parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without any partisan dogma or categorization, to take from each party what is best for our country and put it into practice.
Do you consider yourself more of a right-wing or left-wing man?
From a Czech point of view, I feel like people put me more to the left.
For me, whether it's a little left or right, it doesn't really matter.
For me, the important thing is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not whether people are left or right, but to bring people together.
I am always in favour of any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or the SDGs, and I am equally impartial against bad ideas.
Do you get angry when someone says you're a populist?
But doesn 't what you said prove it ?
When you draw up a business plan in a company, you also have a certain optimal goal and vision.
You're trying to get close.
Some may call it populism, but all the proposals I'm talking about have been implemented around the world and talked about by renowned experts.
But without the support of parliament, you're left with nothing but slogans.
You won't survive in politics for long with that.
Do you think that if you go to people and talk to them, you will succeed in imposing, for example, material and criminal liability?
I don't have any other choice.
I have to convince the politicians, the journalists and the public and try to rally them to my side in order to impose it.
If I were elected President, it would not be a problem to broadcast my request to the chairmen of parliamentary parties to legislate on the material and criminal liability of politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors on live television.
If so, they should explain why they do not want to.
When there is a strong personality who identifies the abuses, it will be possible to put pressure on the political scene.
Take, for example, the direct election of the president, which was achieved through public pressure.
I confess, without hesitation, that I am an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I'm trying to find allies for my views and visions.
I've just entered politics and I'm trying to get the majority's support for my program.
I'm trying to get things done on my own, and if it doesn't work out, I'm gonna quit in six years and go back to the private sector.
It's like Okamura is supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know that one person cannot make a difference, so I went to a number of celebrities and asked them to run for the Senate as well.
I met Radim Jančura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
At least I supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencová who exposed the oil fraud.
I came here because people are really unhappy, but now I'm hesitant.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote and what they did, for the most part, was to vote for a representative of the establishment.
In the Senate, we're the only two independents.
The people have elected a Senate that will hardly be able to impose changes.
I will fight for my vision, for example, the direct election of mayors and prefects.
Are you planning to start your own party?
No, not yet, because I don't have time to check every potential member's past for stainless, and then I don't have the financial means.
I don't have any money for my presidential campaign either, I only have twenty thousand in my "transparent" account.
You don't have any money?
You're talking about tax returns, what's yours?
I estimate the value of my personal property at about 60 million.
I have a land in Prague worth 25 million, an apartment worth 10 million, another apartment worth 8 million, a collection of art worth about 10 million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Škoda Superb worth 1 million and a few million on my account.
By the way, I own an Aston Martin, because it was a childhood dream: I always liked James Bond, who drove cars, was gallant with women and fought against evil and abuse.
You drive an Aston Martin, you have a fortune worth $60 million, and you don't have any money for your campaign?
You want to change the Republic but you don 't want to invest your own money ?
That's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million for this campaign.
Should I go into debt?
I've already invested $2.5 million in the campaign.
The fact that I have no sponsors clearly shows that my programme is not attracting much interest.
I don't have to pay for this campaign out of my own pocket.
My campaign expenses are largely covered by the salary I'll receive as a senator.
But I couldn't live with it, for example, paying for my son's English school, which costs 30 thousand a month.
If my only goal was to make money, I wouldn't run for any elections.
So you 're going to continue your business activities to make a living ?
Didn't you say you'd put your activities on hold?
But this is not related to the amount of this remuneration.
As promised, I have reduced my activities to a certain extent.
For example, my assistant will be running the travel agency in the spring.
People would want me to be a Samaritan saving the Republic.
I must have something to live on.
What was your usual monthly salary when you were a contractor?
I was earning and I'm still earning between two hundred and four hundred thousand.
If I were president, I'd end my business activities.
You can find this interview in the Saturday edition of the newspaper Práva.
The architects of MVRDV prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination.To see for yourself, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it looks very futuristic, something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer engineer at a large company nearby, says: "Yes, it is indeed a beautiful building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everybody has the Internet, an iPad, e-books.
No one goes to one of those sleazy libraries of their own free will, does he?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping village that has nothing attractive on the outskirts of Rotterdam, has a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 people has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brain, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture by reproducing the seven fictitious bridges on the euro notes in the form of beautiful miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has been limited.
The city authorities realized that there was only one way to get their hands on the statistics - by building a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam architects' office MVRDV, master of bold stick drawings and designer of spirited and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, puzzled and shouldering, the disgruntled Maas piled up his choice of books in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his activist-backed speech with a: "Dear Common!"
Here is my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the $30 million mountain came crashing down.
The building is part of a revitalization project which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus this small, dull village, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunningly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest that it houses a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado from the book under the cheese bell.
Although an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, the real joys of reading and architecture are unlocked when you step on the floor of the building and discover its topography.
The interior, entirely made of glass, is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant light fixtures speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The city atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking for the eyes of the public benches, the dogs and the little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and books.
"Normally, the library shelves are along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal", explains Willy Maas.
We've completely upended the conventional spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been carefully designed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental centre and the technical centre of the building.
One particular beauty is the library's black beams, which are sometimes sheets, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircases.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the most skilled architects and building engineers don't want unfamiliar materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a reply to the Standard.
One day we found ad hoc agricultural waste in a frizzled farm.
In the Netherlands, one millimeter thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time, in such quantities, into plates four centimetres thick.
Under heat and pressure, the 'Landbouwplastic' (KPL) changes colour and turns into a dark, homogeneous and durable material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 metres, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
These create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal humidity level of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology", says Trouborst.
The building's temperature is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun shines for only a short time inside, even on fine days.
Thick wooden beams mounted across the glass facade serve as a sunshade, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds will take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic computer scientist mentioned earlier, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there too.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul at last found" by Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This was a way to fill the empty library, which was not yet fully filled - it now contains 70,000 books.
The concept is a success.
The rays are pouring in from all sides.
According to architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library".
"I think our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration".
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline called, in professional jargon, "creating an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page in literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
It is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role".
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of the State of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why would you do that?
Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be careful, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to introduce a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are thus facing several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find that role, but they are on the way to a more 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Britain
What, then, does the term 'normal' foreign policy mean in practice for Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, i.e. by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers: Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Has this economic interest influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and the abstention at the UN vote?
Germany has first of all important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
So Berlin must be careful not to offend the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
I would not, however, attach too much importance to this, because it is not a relationship which is exclusively one-sided.
But this is at least a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by abstaining from important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans understand the German position perfectly.
I therefore think that the rift is not as serious as it was in the case of Libya.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are mixed.
The United States, on the other hand, has made its veto clear.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and most European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic political scene in America.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is far from over-enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Does Germany have difficulty in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States with the position of the major European partners?
I don't think it makes things any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must assert their singular position.
That is what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that Germany will be a driving force in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relations with Israel.
This has always been a delicate question.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they must play a role which will give them more independence.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is she still having trouble taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still having difficulty in playing a bigger role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany decides to weigh more, there is a lot of anti-German sentiment.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it's always the same problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States in this respect.
She has to deal with neighbors and very different opinions, and that is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European politics is diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling that void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant and even if they're less appreciated, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyze the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark is thus protected so that the undertaking bearing the name cannot bring an action.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd win.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", explains Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer with the firm Taylor Wessing specializing in property rights infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes on my desk.
The copyists only need a few more letters to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we're going to register Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we're going to register Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as Puma, the sportswear manufacturer, are also legally copied.
Pattloch opens a file containing the records made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma brand, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In large cities, you can find multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually only counterfeit goods.
The Pattloch case, however, is different: his clients instruct him to tackle the fact that the Chinese trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name which is already protected in another country.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", a related brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is the term used to describe women who marry wealthy men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, and we have to fight this trend", Pattloch demands.
"Brand is sweetened, singularity is lost, reputational damage is enormous".
The financial losses and legal costs for the sectors concerned are in the millions, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis firm CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury market in the world, with an annual turnover of EUR 15 billion.
However, it is not easy to remove questionable registrations from the trade mark register and these procedures are costly.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch mentions cases in which the court dismissed the complaint because after a long period of time the name under criticism had become a "market reality".
Pattloch tells us that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, as he would have damaged his brand in China.
In this area, sometimes the law of the jungle prevails.
Famous cases also involve graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought out concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That's why the Chinese can use a logo that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the acquirer of Volvo, used a blue and white logo that was reminiscent of BMW's.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost to beachgoers from Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the famous crocodile's gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO Trade Mark Office in Beijing, however, admits that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office was reportedly transformed last year from a "work emergency to a return to normalcy".
The number of unprocessed opposition proceedings has thus fallen by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were reportedly closed, an increase of 75% over the previous year.
However, 81,500 procedures remain pending at the office.
The cost of action
