Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of mistreatment that Bradley Manning was allegedly subjected to while in custody.
The trial concerns Manning's detention at a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to dismiss the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction occurred under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of initiating the largest leak of classified information in the history of the U.S. military -- missed many opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he claims he suffered while in military detention.
In a cross-examination of Manning during a preliminary hearing at Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Major Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- in a hearing, the defense filed a motion demanding that Manning's case be dismissed on the grounds that the abduction occurred under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently harsh punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide while in custody.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were later published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms the officers had filled out after meeting Manning, while he was being held at the Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein discussed the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in prison was generally "very professional".
The forms do not record any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns orally about certain problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the problems raised.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after they had addressed the concerns), and that didn't mean I hadn't raised problems", Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had convened to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention at the meeting was to have his restrictive status amended to indicate a "risk of injury".
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was doing well, and I wanted to have my status removed... so that I could have a better quality of life from my point of view", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at Marine Corps Base Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide while in Kuwait and once fainted from the heat.
He added that it was very distressing not to have been informed of what was about to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage", Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours, sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only things he had were a mattress, a blanket, tights, clothes, and his glasses.
He tried to keep moving, as sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also stated that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about the treatment Manning suffered in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about an allegation in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questioning on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard's order that he should drop his blanket that could have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he was supposedly trying to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic band of his underwear or his flip flops to hurt himself, but he didn't.
