The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to lesser offenses and fight for the dropping of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention for all inmates at Quantico.
The charges brought against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and transmission of information relating to national defense.
If all the charges are upheld, he's facing life in prison.
