To measure this, researchers developed a "boredom predisposition scale" in the 1980's.
The scale includes statements like, "Many of the tasks I do are repetitive and monotonous", and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all".
Using such a scale, researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and they need many and varied stimulations.
