The world's toughest job: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four dollars, volcano-carryers in Indonesia risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work hell.
That is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the Indonesian island of East Java.
He has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas from the earth's interior solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large stones of sulfur, weighing some 70 pounds, he places them in two bamboo baskets and carries them on his shoulders through the steep paths.
It is only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb the distance at tortoise speed, keeping their balance and measuring their steps so as not to trip and fall into the cliff.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell dead from the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur mined.
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and they walk the three-kilometer-long (3-mile-long) stretch of the scales, which a mining company has installed a little below, at an altitude of 1,800 feet [1,850 m].
The company, PT Candi Ngrimbi, has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, so to speak, its employees, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupees (€5 cents) per kilo of sulphur.
She then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (US$83) because the mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees ($1,500) each trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each one takes him three hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (US$11.50) at the end of the day.
Although this may seem like a misery for such a superhuman effort, it's three times what he would earn in the field.
"The income of miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees ($1,25) a day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees ($1,35)", says the porter who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not that difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto suffers from asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and eyes irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he's spent three years of his life defying the danger on the Kawah Ijen, but sulfur has already started to pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and irritation of the eyes from the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
It's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French", he promises in a more than acceptable English.
This friendly, intelligent young man, who is worn out by life, might be a tour guide, a waiter, or a receptionist in a hotel, but instead he is doing the work of a mule.
He shares a piece of unsanitary wood with other bearers, rises every day at two in the morning because the sulfur keeps gushing at night, when his characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by illuminating himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
Some 400 porters load the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanised the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work for themselves and are paid by weight.
They also do not get a penny of the 30,000 rupees ($2.50) per camera, plus the 15,000 rupees ($1.20) entrance fee that the park guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is done for animals, not for humans", protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old heavy-duty porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for 30 years, since he left high school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kilograms, and he says he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his three sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of serious illness - in addition to their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unainik can only carry 50 kilos.
Each day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away, along a goat-trail filled with weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life", says Unainik, opening his mouth wide, revealing several missing teeth.
The oldest of her five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur porter.
Time passes, but misery endures from generation to generation. One of the most difficult jobs in the world, that of the human mules at Kawah Ijen.
