Singaporeans blame the absence of children on careers, stress and the cost of access to property.
"The population of Singapore must grow".
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let's fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem improbable that these words come from an advertisement for mint pills, but despite this, or perhaps because of it, the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a pin in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way through this ad.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do "their national duty".
It's only for the Internet, so we've been able to make it fun and entertaining.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in terms of births, so we felt that this was a topic we needed to address.
We knew the government had tried a lot of things like throwing pheromone perfumes or having speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, what's more creative to solve this problem than to turn it into a rap song?
1.2 children
The Singapore government doesn't take it so lightly.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure for marriage and fathers provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative rulers and strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, according to its national population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 as the renewal rate was in 1976.
So why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policies at the National Population Division, says that this is due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities".
"It has given people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family", she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at dramatically increasing immigration to counter the declining population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that show little disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are accused of pushing down wages and not integrating.
Increasing immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore last year had its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem by introducing quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unintended Consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to prevent many small houses from being built.
For example, it has started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square metres and their sale is very successful.
However, authorities are concerned that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, the general manager of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these houses are built much faster than larger ones.
For that reason, it's much more profitable for our cash.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put in the wheel if they wanted to offer too small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards raising the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district in the centre, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
