What's private offline is private online.
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Spanish Royal Academy, it is the quality of the private sphere or "the sphere of private life that we can protect from intrusion".
What is private property for under 16s?
How can this definition be applied in everyday life and on social media?
Does he realize the dangers of posting events online that he would not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level with "password and username" when applied to social networks.
"I won't reveal my most personal secrets in a post", says ten-year-old Jorge, who has been using Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail, and Windows Live Messenger for two years to explain the meaning of the word privacy.
"They're very secret, my mother may know them but not everyone", he says.
I post funny pictures or games on FB.
I also chat with my friends.
"I won't share any of my pictures or anyone who's being silly", he says.
The boy recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene pictures, naked people, crimes, or humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on Facebook and his 9 followers on Twitter.
Most of them are family.
His mother's one of them, she knows the password to one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they're answering me, I'm just posting them", he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to distant relatives or with my friends, in a fast way", he says.
He says he would never accept a request from a stranger.
Nor would he trust anyone who would recommend a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask accounts, on the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people on his friend list.
"I don't worry about it because we have something in common, for example music", he says.
The boy said that no one approached him or asked for his address or phone number.
"If they pressured me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account", he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we now know as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A friend of mine's relative was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was", he says.
The victim, according to José, didn't close his account.
"He only passed it on in private".
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a secure manner.
Unlike Jorge, this young man posted pictures of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would if I was angry or upset.
"Even though I know it's cyberbullying", he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a degree in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents, one must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet started as a way of finding information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
Porras reports that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in education from Yale University and is the author of the book "Natives and Digital Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are them, the children and young people who are born with technology.
"We, the digital immigrants, are there to teach them, while we ourselves are learning", she says.
He adds that the subject is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what is or is not appropriate to disclose, publish or say at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so".
"We also ask them to be selective when what they care about most is being popular, having thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences", she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and teenagers confidentiality is to use thought-provoking questions.
"Telling them not to do it is no good", she says.
Then Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like them to post a picture of you like a friend you posted?
Do you know what other people post about you?
When you identify party photos, do you ask other people's permission to identify them?
Also, does everyone need to know what you're doing every second?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social networks", she says.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor and primary school teacher and counselor, says that it is vital that parents carefully read the terms and conditions for using social networking sites.
Understanding each term will provide a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an Internet account.
"For example, age and what is allowed to share or publish", he says.
Guardia says it's vital to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VIth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it had been announced earlier and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit closed, then claimed that it would be published at some point on the website of the Peruvian government.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been explained by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Access to information on the summit by journalists has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the audio-free video of the presidential meeting with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The few information that circulated among journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the governments of Unasur that attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released on the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American-Arab Summit (ASPA) and on that occasion, although it was urged by the press, it also did not release the so-called Lima Declaration, as had been previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the access to information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also concluded with Chile and Peru agreeing jointly to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleadings of both parties in the trial Lima has filed against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and implement the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today", President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts", added President Piñera, shaking hands with President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact, in which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of the international court, following a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the ouster of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The mandate read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would take "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He said that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to low-cost internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to foresee a better future for our people", President Humala concluded.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connectivity of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects were for Peru and were located on the transverse axis of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and in good relations with its neighbours, was another topic discussed at the Summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before the start of the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", President Santos said.
"We will review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will require a discussion with that country", he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", added President Santos.
President Santos and President Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen defence dialogue and consensus in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship", says Rafael Correa.
