Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay in Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the body "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality, "it would destroy the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considered as 'perfectly relevant' the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which would strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not being respected.
It's a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We must solve them as a whole in order to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the successful resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and said that it was "beneficial for Latin America to bring the matter before international bodies if both countries agree to accept any firm ruling".
Referring to the possibility of his running for a third consecutive term in the forthcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, he said he sees this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa has said that if he loses the February 2013 primary, he will retire from public life.
On a personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as those in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be solved through political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this eventual victory but we must accept this responsibility", he said.
