If we ever lose, I'll lose too.
"It's my decision", he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse in the health of President Chávez", he commented.
The Ecuadorian Head of State attended the Sixth Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) in Lima today, which ended with a call for better regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths are now the result of late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he tested positive for HIV.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head", he said, referring to the time of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and started to find out about it and his tenacity was so great that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the longest-serving patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), where he was admitted in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something that was hard to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options, and more stigmas.
So even the director of one IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was voiceless".
In those days, AIDS was death.
Today, it is possible to survive the syndrome and enjoy a good quality of life.
However, many people, unaware of their illness, still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "deplete" their immune system and fall victim to opportunistic infections.
31 years after the start of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he takes as reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious disease and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system impairment patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for those with CD4 levels of 200 and up to 50 years for those with CD4 levels of 500.
Simply put, this means that for someone diagnosed as HIV positive at age 25, "as long as he remains under control, he can live safely until age 75", explained the scientist interviewed.
To put this progress into context, we must know that the average life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years.
While it is true that the death rate has decreased significantly in recent years, in Mexico the number of deaths from AIDS increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the annual report of UNAIDS), but it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I think the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
For the last 12 years at least, we've never run out of drugs, and the problem is that patients come in very late stages because they don't know they're infected, or they find out at the late stages of the disease.
It gives us a clear fact: "Nine out of ten patients arrive with an opportunistic infection, and what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for that, to offer mass screening tests to all people who ask".
Specialists and members of the Jalisco State Council for AIDS Prevention (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to take his test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done so and that, despite his young age, he was already HIV positive and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you find out you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't care.
"If I'm going to die, I'd better have a good time three times a week", they say, but I don't.
The change has been good, I eat right, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, all his parents know is that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I am co-responsible, I take care of myself and the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, through his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Let them get tested, if they've taken risks, the sooner they know they're HIV positive, the better, and if they're already diagnosed, they need to know that you can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the average citizen, argues Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packs of a hundred, that's very good, but the result is that even today, some people don't have access to condoms", he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are teenagers.
The question, "What are you going to do with it?" asked sarcastically and with judgment by social workers, counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
He suggests that this inefficient distribution be refocused; that condoms should not only be sold at counters but be found in public toilets and in places frequented by young people.
This is not about promoting promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying for girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González said when asked if there would be condom distribution within his administration.
"That's not how sex works, the best thing is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active", he said.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cases of AIDS (12,158 and 1,317 HIV).
The state is the 4th largest in the country in terms of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in terms of HIV patients.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are blood-borne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for every recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who are unaware of it.
A judgment upheld on appeal by a US court overlooks the restructuring of the Vitro group's debt agreed through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a bad precedent for all domestic companies with branches in the neighbouring country and solvency problems.
So it seems that the survival procedures of the Mexican companies authorized by the laws are not valid in the star-studded country, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment handed down on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of an embargo on their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to take the case to the U.S. Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the trial judge states that creditors must register under the U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, states that the main proceedings are the commercial bankruptcy of Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the intercompany vote, which recognised in the critical mass of the commercial bankruptcy the debts contracted by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws allow this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
There are half a dozen examples here, among them Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the votes of the subsidiaries remained, the Vitro creditors who fought against this in the US courts, i.e. the 'vulture' funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have won a majority in any event.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A fact that the appellate court omitted.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation it had been in since 2008 without stopping at the severe economic crisis facing the United States, which was spilling over the costs to the country.
For the time being, the González Sada family company will appeal to the same court of appeal to have the vote taken in its entirety, i.e. with the five judges, since only three had voted.
The insurance claim will claim non-prosperity and require review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court of Justice.
The most serious was that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the court") detailing the procedure followed by Vitro under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, stating that this exempted it from the agreements signed by the two countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
It also notes that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules laid down for cross-border insolvency cases, which guarantee fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-party car-rail, they knock Vitro out and they knock the country out.
General accounting
The complaints of the Mexican Aviation Society's unions against the company's former boss, Gastón Azcárraga Andrade, were kept quiet for several months, he was accused of fraudulent administration, the Pilots' Union Association has already run into problems.
The court, headed by Carlos Díaz Chávez Morineau, has just filed a criminal complaint against the National Banking and Securities Commission, which is accused of obstruction of justice.
According to him, the inspection authority systematically denied that it had provided information to the Attorney General of the Republic on an operation carried out by the contractor to withdraw 198 million pesos from the F/589 trust fund of IXE Bank on behalf of Mexicana de Aviación.
The funds would have been used to purchase shares in the Professional Hotel Administration.
As everyone knows, Azcárraga Andrade is the main shareholder of the Posadas hotel chain.
