Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
Basketball world-trotter "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life connected to the field and, thanks to it, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much knowledge of local basketball history as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage sentenced him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a minor league player, a national basketball team player, a manager and executive of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s", Reyes recalls during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating when he makes that claim.
The walls of his house, decorated almost entirely with photographs and memorabilia that recall his extraordinary itinerary, bear this out.
Bayamon in the heart
Of all his memories, those he cherishes most are those that remind him of his time as a player with the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I was lucky enough to compete in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or manager.
It has been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over the team", Reyes says.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was the manager here at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, and he said, "I have a big player for you. He's six feet tall.
Do you want it?"
That's how Mincy started, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who had been naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He rejoiced in the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At the time, he preferred to enjoy his and Mincy's burdens on the national team.
I remember when we first won it for the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth and should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian referee hadn't made us play the last game again", Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
