Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman (born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas) became known worldwide for his leading role as John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a ruthless, fearsome, manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press by "Dallas" production company Warner Bros.
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most", the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and its sequel, was with Hagman when he died at a Dallas hospital, his press secretary, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, loving and talented, and I'm gonna miss him so much.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest", Gray said in a statement.
Doctors diagnosed Larry Hagman with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and he admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and had a transplant.
Years before "Dallas", Hagman had made his television debut as an ordinary guy in the NBC series "Jinny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In this one, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among her film roles are critically acclaimed roles in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was through his masterful rendition of the deliciously abominable J.R. that Larry Hagman achieved his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?" invented to keep the suspense around an emotional episode in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, generated worldwide speculation and millions of dollars in betting.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers were in front of their screens, making "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. had gotten her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she didn't leave town, but other people had reasons to assault her, too.
Hagman played Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable but charismaticly smiling man: a dishonest entrepreneur and unfaithful husband who was trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) committed.
"I know what would be an epitaph for J.R"., Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "This is Honest Citizen J.R. Ewing".
